Configuring Network Policies

1. What is a Network Policy?
Definition
A NetworkPolicy is a Kubernetes/OpenShift resource that controls which pods can communicate with other pods.
It works like a firewall inside the cluster.
Example control:
Pod A → Pod B  (allowed)
Pod C → Pod B  (blocked)
________________________________________
2. Default Network Behavior in OpenShift
By default:
All pods can communicate with all pods
Example:
namespace1/podA → namespace2/podB  ✔ allowed
namespace2/podC → namespace1/podD  ✔ allowed
Meaning:
Open network
This is not secure for production systems.
________________________________________
3. Why Network Policies Are Needed
Enterprise applications require network isolation.
Example architecture:
Frontend → Backend → Database
Security requirement:
Frontend → Backend  ✔
Backend → Database  ✔
Frontend → Database ✖
Network policies enforce this rule.
________________________________________
4. Network Policies Use Labels (Not IP)
Traditional firewall:
Allow IP 10.0.0.1
Kubernetes NetworkPolicy:
Allow pods with label app=frontend
Why labels?
Pods are dynamic:
Pod deleted → new IP assigned
Labels stay constant.
Example pod label:
app=frontend
tier=backend
role=db
________________________________________
5. Network Policy Scope
Network policies operate on:
Pods
Namespaces
Ports
Protocols
They can control:
Ingress  → incoming traffic
Egress   → outgoing traffic
________________________________________
6. Important Limitation
Network policies do not block host networking pods on the same node.
Example:
Ingress router pods
Monitoring pods
These may bypass some restrictions unless explicitly allowed.
________________________________________
7. Types of Network Policies in OpenShift
OpenShift supports 2 types:
1️⃣ NetworkPolicy (NP)
Scope:
Namespace
Created by:
Developers
Namespace admins
Used for:
Application level security
________________________________________
2️⃣ AdminNetworkPolicy (ANP)
Scope:
Cluster wide
Created by:
Cluster administrators
Used for:
Global security rules
________________________________________
8. Evaluation Order
OpenShift networking engine:
OVN-Kubernetes
It evaluates policies in tiers.
Tier 1 → AdminNetworkPolicy
Tier 2 → NetworkPolicy
Evaluation flow:
Traffic request
      ↓
AdminNetworkPolicy checked
      ↓
If match → allow/deny
      ↓
If no match → NetworkPolicy checked
Meaning:
ANP has higher priority
________________________________________
9. Network Policies Are Additive
Multiple policies can apply to the same pod.
Allowed traffic = union of all policies.
Example:
Policy A allows:
Frontend → Backend
Policy B allows:
Monitoring → Backend
Final allowed traffic:
Frontend → Backend
Monitoring → Backend
________________________________________
10. Default Deny Policy (Very Important)
Best practice:
First deny everything
Then allow required traffic
Example YAML:
kind: NetworkPolicy
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
metadata:
  name: default-deny
spec:
  podSelector: {}
Explanation
Field	Meaning
podSelector {}	apply to all pods
no ingress rules	block all incoming traffic
Effect:
Nothing can access the pods
Unless another policy allows it.
________________________________________
11. Basic Network Policy Structure
Example:
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-frontend
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: backend
  ingress:
  - from:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          app: frontend
Meaning:
Frontend pods can access backend pods
________________________________________
12. Communication Between Namespaces
Namespaces can also be selected using labels.
Example label a namespace:
Command:
oc label namespace network-1 network=network-1
Meaning:
Add label network=network-1
________________________________________
13. Example Policy (Cross Namespace)
Policy in network-1 namespace
kind: NetworkPolicy
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
metadata:
  name: network-1-policy
  namespace: network-1
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      deployment: product-catalog
This selects pods:
deployment=product-catalog
________________________________________
Ingress Rule
ingress:
- from:
Defines who can connect.
________________________________________
Namespace Selector
namespaceSelector:
  matchLabels:
    network: network-2
Meaning:
Allow traffic from namespace network-2
________________________________________
Pod Selector
podSelector:
  matchLabels:
    role: qa
Meaning:
Only pods with label role=qa
________________________________________
Port Restriction
ports:
- port: 8080
  protocol: TCP
Meaning:
Only allow TCP 8080
________________________________________
Final Rule
Allowed traffic:
network-2 namespace
        ↓
pods with role=qa
        ↓
product-catalog pods
        ↓
TCP port 8080
________________________________________
14. Less Restrictive Policy
Example in network-2 namespace
podSelector: {}
Means:
All pods in namespace
Rule:
namespaceSelector:
  matchLabels:
    network: network-1
Meaning:
Allow any pod from network-1 namespace
________________________________________
15. Logical AND vs OR
This is very important for exams.
________________________________________
Logical AND
Example:
from:
- namespaceSelector:
    matchLabels:
      network: dev
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: mobile
Meaning BOTH must match:
Namespace label = dev
AND
Pod label = mobile
________________________________________
Logical OR
Example:
from:
- namespaceSelector:
    matchLabels:
      network: dev
- podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: mobile
Meaning:
Namespace = dev
OR
Pod label = mobile
________________________________________
16. Allowing OpenShift Router Access
When network policies block everything, routes may stop working.
Because router pods live in:
openshift-ingress namespace
Allow router traffic:
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-from-openshift-ingress
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  ingress:
  - from:
    - namespaceSelector:
        matchLabels:
          policy-group.network.openshift.io/ingress: ""
Meaning:
Allow traffic from router pods
________________________________________
17. Allow Monitoring Access
Monitoring namespace:
openshift-monitoring
Policy:
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-from-openshift-monitoring
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  ingress:
  - from:
    - namespaceSelector:
        matchLabels:
          network.openshift.io/policy-group: monitoring
Meaning:
Allow Prometheus monitoring
________________________________________
18. AdminNetworkPolicy (Cluster Level)
AdminNetworkPolicy allows cluster-wide security rules.
API:
policy.networking.k8s.io/v1alpha1
Example:
Block traffic from untrusted namespaces.
apiVersion: policy.networking.k8s.io/v1alpha1
kind: AdminNetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: block-untrusted
________________________________________
Priority
priority: 100
Range:
1–100
Lower number = higher priority.
________________________________________
Subject
subject:
  namespaceSelector: {}
Meaning:
Apply rule to all namespaces
________________________________________
Deny Rule
ingress:
- from:
  - namespaceSelector:
      matchLabels:
        untrusted: true
  action: Deny
Meaning:
Block traffic from namespaces labeled:

untrusted=true
________________________________________
19. Example: Deny All Traffic to Sensitive Namespace
kind: AdminNetworkPolicy
spec:
  priority: 10
  subject:
    namespaces:
      matchLabels:
        sensitive: true
  ingress: []
Meaning:
No traffic allowed
To namespaces with label:
sensitive=true
________________________________________
20. Example: Allow Egress to External Database
Example:
egress:
- to:
  - ipBlock:
      cidr: 10.0.0.0/24
Meaning:
Pods can connect to:
10.0.0.0/24 network
________________________________________
Port Restriction
ports:
- port: 3306
  protocol: TCP
Meaning:
Allow MySQL database access
________________________________________
21. Important oc Commands
Create network policy:
oc apply -f policy.yaml
List policies:
oc get networkpolicy
Describe policy:
oc describe networkpolicy
Delete policy:
oc delete networkpolicy policy-name
Label namespace:
oc label namespace dev network=dev
